		<item>
		<title>Inside the spam call machine behind Nigeria&#8217;s digital lending boom</title>
		<link>https://techcabal.com/2026/04/29/inside-nigeria-spam-calls-problem/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Fancy Goodman]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Wed, 29 Apr 2026 14:37:34 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Features]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[spam calls]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://techcabal.com/?p=185459</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[ Across Nigeria, customers report a barrage of unsolicited promotional calls that disrupt work and invade privacy. ]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<p>In early 2025, Peace*, a research assistant at Covenant University, Ogun State, Southwestern Nigeria, had a health emergency and was short on cash. So, she did the first thing that came to mind: open the OPay app to take a loan.&nbsp;</p>



<p>She navigated to EaseMoni, a loan product offered through OPay&#8217;s lending arm, reviewed the repayment terms, and took some loans. It was ₦6,000 ($4.21) the first time. Then subsequently, ₦24,000 ($16.85).</p>



<p>Peace told TechCabal she repaid the loan before the one-month deadline, closed the app, and moved on. The app, however, did not.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image show-tablet-desktop"><img fetchpriority="high" decoding="async" width="1920" height="1080" 
     	loading="lazy" src="https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-Desktop-06.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-186734" srcset="https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-Desktop-06.jpg 1920w, https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-Desktop-06-300x169.jpg 300w, https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-Desktop-06-1024x576.jpg 1024w, https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-Desktop-06-768x432.jpg 768w, https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-Desktop-06-1536x864.jpg 1536w, https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-Desktop-06-1240x698.jpg 1240w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1920px) 100vw, 1920px" /><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Image source: Chima David/TechCabal</figcaption></figure>



<figure class="wp-block-image mobile-only"><img decoding="async" width="1080" height="1350" 
     	loading="lazy" src="https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-06.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-186733" srcset="https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-06.jpg 1080w, https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-06-240x300.jpg 240w, https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-06-819x1024.jpg 819w, https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-06-768x960.jpg 768w, https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-06-720x900.jpg 720w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1080px) 100vw, 1080px" /><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Image source: Chima David/TechCabal</figcaption></figure>



<p>A few days later, the calls began: an automated and relentless stream of reminders about loan discounts and improved offers.&nbsp;</p>



<p>&#8220;It was like an automated response, [talking] about how my loan discount has increased and how I should apply for a new loan,&#8221; Peace said. &#8220;Mind you, you don’t even have to eventually take the loan for them to bombard you with calls. Just going over the options alone without eventually borrowing will trigger the calls.&#8221;&nbsp;</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image"><img decoding="async" width="1080" height="1920" 
     	loading="lazy" src="https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/Peaces-quote-mobile-1.gif" alt="" class="wp-image-186995"/><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Image source: Lanre Adebanjo/ TechCabal</figcaption></figure>



<p>Months later, she says, the calls have not stopped. &#8220;I’ve been looking for how to turn that [call] thing off, but I can’t find [how to]. It’s so annoying,&#8221; she said.<br>Peace is not alone. In January 2026, Lagos-based growth professional Franklyne Ikediasor <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/franklyne-ikediasor-mba-mcim-60990459/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">shared a curious experience on LinkedIn</a>. After embarking on what he described as a personal “exercise” to understand Nigeria’s booming digital lending market, he found himself at the centre of a flood of unsolicited loan pitches.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image show-tablet-desktop"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1920" height="1080" 
     	loading="lazy" src="https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-Desktop-05.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-186744" srcset="https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-Desktop-05.jpg 1920w, https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-Desktop-05-300x169.jpg 300w, https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-Desktop-05-1024x576.jpg 1024w, https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-Desktop-05-768x432.jpg 768w, https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-Desktop-05-1536x864.jpg 1536w, https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-Desktop-05-1240x698.jpg 1240w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1920px) 100vw, 1920px" /><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Image source: Chima David/TechCabal</figcaption></figure>



<figure class="wp-block-image mobile-only"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1080" height="1350" 
     	loading="lazy" src="https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-05.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-186751" srcset="https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-05.jpg 1080w, https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-05-240x300.jpg 240w, https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-05-819x1024.jpg 819w, https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-05-768x960.jpg 768w, https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-05-720x900.jpg 720w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1080px) 100vw, 1080px" /><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Image source: Chima David/TechCabal</figcaption></figure>



<p>Ikediasor said his experiment allowed him to “test and experience a wide range of loan applications firsthand, reviewing limits, disbursement speed, interest rates, fees, and repayment structures.”</p>



<p>Despite only interacting with a select few platforms, he soon began receiving calls and messages from lenders he had never even heard of, some offering to &#8220;buy over&#8221; his existing loans in a bid to capture his interest.&nbsp;</p>



<p>&#8220;This is clearly illegal,&#8221; Ikediasor told TechCabal,&nbsp; adding that he scanned the 200-page terms-of-use documents for data-sharing loopholes. &#8220;Because I interacted with one application doesn’t mean that data should be passed to another. It’s not just an infringement; it’s predatory.&#8221;</p>



<p>For a researcher and growth professional like Ikediasor, it did not sit right.</p>



<p>&#8220;On average, I get about three [spam] calls a day,&#8221; he said. &#8220;I’ve already had two today. Some are robocalls, but others are human beings speaking to you,&#8221; he said.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image show-tablet-desktop"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1920" height="1080" 
     	loading="lazy" src="https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-Desktop-01.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-186748" srcset="https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-Desktop-01.jpg 1920w, https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-Desktop-01-300x169.jpg 300w, https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-Desktop-01-1024x576.jpg 1024w, https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-Desktop-01-768x432.jpg 768w, https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-Desktop-01-1536x864.jpg 1536w, https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-Desktop-01-1240x698.jpg 1240w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1920px) 100vw, 1920px" /><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Image source: Chima David/TechCabal</figcaption></figure>



<figure class="wp-block-image mobile-only"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1080" height="1350" 
     	loading="lazy" src="https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-01.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-186756" srcset="https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-01.jpg 1080w, https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-01-240x300.jpg 240w, https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-01-819x1024.jpg 819w, https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-01-768x960.jpg 768w, https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-01-720x900.jpg 720w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1080px) 100vw, 1080px" /><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Image source: Chima David/TechCabal</figcaption></figure>



<p>Their experience points to a broader issue: some digital lending companies and telcos have become persistent in calling their users. Across Nigeria, customers report a barrage of unsolicited promotional calls that disrupt work and invade privacy.&nbsp;</p>



<p>For many, the calls continue even after they block numbers, clear outstanding debts, or—in extreme cases—delete the app entirely. Customers say these calls are rarely from human agents. Instead, users claim they are greeted by automated recordings pushing a variety of financial products, from airtime coupons to loan limits.</p>



<p>The implications of automation that persists after an app is deleted go far beyond annoyance. It could allow Nigerians to normalise calls from random, unverified mobile numbers, creating a massive opening for <a href="https://www.cloudflare.com/en-gb/learning/email-security/what-is-vishing/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">vishing</a> (voice phishing) scams, involving tricking people into sharing sensitive information over the phone.&nbsp;</p>



<p>According to a <a href="https://share.google/N9usW5qQ2AQ0qi1Ss" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">2025 report </a>by the International Criminal Police Organisation&nbsp; (INTERPOL), phishing is one of the most frequently reported cybercrimes in Africa. The report stated that cybercriminals regularly impersonate recognised authorities and prominent corporations, exploit widespread unemployment by offering fabricated jobs, and use mobile platforms for prize-related and emergency-based scams.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Since users are accustomed to organisations using unofficial channels to push loans, they are significantly more vulnerable to fraudsters who mimic this tone to hijack accounts.&nbsp;</p>



<p>TechCabal also conducted a broader survey with 120 respondents across Nigeria. 79.2% said they frequently receive spam calls. The respondents include 54 Nigerian employed professionals whose workdays are being systematically interrupted, while the other respondents are students and unemployed young people.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image show-tablet-desktop"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1920" height="1080" 
     	loading="lazy" src="https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-Desktop-07.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-186742" srcset="https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-Desktop-07.jpg 1920w, https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-Desktop-07-300x169.jpg 300w, https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-Desktop-07-1024x576.jpg 1024w, https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-Desktop-07-768x432.jpg 768w, https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-Desktop-07-1536x864.jpg 1536w, https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/04/OPAY-Spam-Call-Assets-Desktop-07-1240x698.jpg 1240w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1920px) 100vw, 1920px" /><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Image source: Chima David/TechCabal</figcaption></figure>



<figure class="wp-block-image mobile-only"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1080" height="1350" 
